            "last_activity_date": 1269782518,
            "creation_date": 1269782518,
            "body": "<p>See for example \"Encapsulating non-database data resources as DAO classes\" section here: <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://java.sun.com/blueprints/patterns/DAO.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://java.sun.com/blueprints/patterns/DAO.html<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2533026,
            "question_id": 2532985
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/eeec80237213c91e5bab56b77ac5b8ca?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 16878,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 37213,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/37213/duffymo",
                "reputation": 309604,
                "display_name": "duffymo",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269783299,
            "creation_date": 1269783299,
            "body": "<p>Since DAOs only express CRUD operations in terms of objects, without ever referring to their data source, I can't see why this is a question.  If your DAO begins with an interface that meets those criteria clients need not know whether or not it's implemented in terms of XML or a relational database.<\/p>\n\n<p>.NET's LINQ manages to turn that trick.  Maybe it's another design that you can emulate for this problem.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2533069,
            "question_id": 2532985
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a14850281f19396480bdba4aab2d52ef?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 41465,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 120513,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/120513/daff",
                "reputation": 44355,
                "display_name": "Daff",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269783356,
            "creation_date": 1269783356,
            "body": "<p>Your DAO offers generic methods that are - as you already said - independent of any datasource. Therefore you create a DAO interface and then just provide different implementations. Other classes then only use the DAO interface.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public interface DummyDao\n{\n    Dummy getDummy(String id);\n}\n\npublic class SqlDummyDao implements DummyDao\n{\n    public Dummy getDummy(String id)\n    {\n        // Do sql stuff and mapping to dummy bean here\n    }\n}\n\npublic class XmlDummyDao implements DummyDao\n{\n    public Dummy getDummy(String id)\n    {\n        XmlDocument xml = fetchRemoteXml(id);\n        // do xml mapping to dummy bean here\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 2533072,
            "question_id": 2532985
        }
    ],
